National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan met with Kim Sung-han, National Security Advisor of the Republic of Korea (ROK), to discuss preparations for the upcoming State Visit by ROK President Yoon Suk Yeol and First Lady Kim Keon Hee. The visit will celebrate the 70th anniversary of the U.S.-ROK alliance and aim to deepen political, economic, security, and people-to-people ties between the two countries. Sullivan also welcomed the historic breakthrough between ROK and Japan to resolve historical issues, which opens the door to increased cooperation between these key allies. They discussed maintaining close cooperation to enhance security ties in response to the changing threat environment in the Indo-Pacific region. Sullivan reaffirmed the United States' commitment to the security of the ROK and the region and providing extended deterrence through U.S. defense capabilities. They condemned the Democratic People's Republic of Korea's (DPRK) continued destabilizing activity and stressed the need for the international community, including allies and partners at the United Nations, to limit the DPRK's ability to advance its unlawful weapons of mass destruction (WMD) program, which threatens regional stability. They also talked about the importance of concerted efforts to promote peace and stability globally. They condemned Russia's war in Ukraine and discussed the need to continue supplying assistance to the Ukrainian people. The two advisors emphasized ongoing cooperation to advance and protect their countries' technology leadership, address economic coercion, and tackle vulnerabilities in supply chains, telecommunications infrastructure, and cyber networks to ensure the continued prosperity of allies and partners.